WEBVTT



00:00:00.736 --> 00:00:04.576
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:00:04.384 --> 00:00:09.824
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:18.784
using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:00:18.848 --> 00:00:27.040
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:36.448
Today, we invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the Gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:00:39.168 --> 00:00:46.592
Peace be with you. Friends, for this 22nd Sunday of Ordinary Time, I want to talk to you about a very, very important theme.

00:00:46.784 --> 00:00:50.496
Namely, the theme of pride and its antidote.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:52.576
Now, I say very important because...

00:00:52.416 --> 00:00:54.912
I don't know a spiritual teacher.

00:00:55.104 --> 00:00:56.960
Who doesn't say

00:00:56.800 --> 00:01:00.416
The fundamental problem we have is pride.

00:01:00.736 --> 00:01:04.096
And of course, they're getting us from the great biblical witness.

00:01:04.096 --> 00:01:06.368
What goes wrong with us? Well,

00:01:06.144 --> 00:01:07.104
The.

00:01:07.008 --> 00:01:11.392
Most serious of the deadly sins, the capital

00:01:11.168 --> 00:01:13.024
Of the capital sins.

00:01:12.992 --> 00:01:16.736
Is recognized universally by the spiritual teachers as

00:01:16.992 --> 00:01:25.632
Pride. Now, I know we tend to say, oh, it's lust. We tend to associate sexual sin with the, you know, supreme problem. Right.

00:01:25.728 --> 00:01:31.072
Don't write me letters. Lust is a deadly sin. Sexual sin is a serious problem. Don't get me wrong.

00:01:30.784 --> 00:01:36.096
But there's not one spiritual teacher that would say lust or sexual sin is the highest.

00:01:36.192 --> 00:01:38.816
No, no, the highest one, the most...

00:01:38.688 --> 00:01:40.096
Deadly one.

00:01:40.224 --> 00:01:41.952
Is pride.

00:01:41.984 --> 00:01:44.160
So the Bible talks about it a lot.

00:01:44.608 --> 00:01:46.304
Well, what is pride?

00:01:46.592 --> 00:01:51.840
My go-to man usually is Thomas Aquinas. He says it's inordinate or excessive

00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:52.928
self-love.

00:01:52.864 --> 00:02:00.256
So is there a legitimate self-love, sure, but an inordinate or excessive self-love, that's pride.

00:02:00.256 --> 00:02:02.496
So Augustine, I've often quoted him.

00:02:03.104 --> 00:02:05.216
Kervatos in se.

00:02:05.088 --> 00:02:08.864
When you're caved in around yourself, that's

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:10.400
The attitude of pride

00:02:10.912 --> 00:02:15.232
I think this way maybe it's an attitude that prevents us

00:02:15.872 --> 00:02:19.328
From real contact with reality.

00:02:19.904 --> 00:02:24.896
It's being caved in upon the self. It's a self-regard.

00:02:24.896 --> 00:02:26.848
That prevents me

00:02:27.136 --> 00:02:29.888
From getting in touch with reality.

00:02:29.952 --> 00:02:35.168
It's like living in a very cramped, narrow spiritual space.

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:44.448
Maybe I'd use the metaphor of the black hole that draws all things into itself. So instead of going out to the world,

00:02:45.184 --> 00:02:48.544
The world's drawn into the little narrow space.

00:02:48.608 --> 00:02:51.712
Of my self-preoccupation.

00:02:52.064 --> 00:02:56.768
That's pride. And that's why it's such a deadly sin.

00:02:57.568 --> 00:02:58.976
Where does it come from?

00:02:59.168 --> 00:03:04.352
I've always liked Paul Tillich's answer. Tillich said, "Pride is born of fear."

00:03:04.704 --> 00:03:05.856
And think about it.

00:03:06.464 --> 00:03:10.304
To be finite is to be afraid. You know, we're vulnerable, right?

00:03:10.656 --> 00:03:11.936
we're threatened.

00:03:11.936 --> 00:03:15.872
We're not self-sufficient. And so we have an instinct that

00:03:15.776 --> 00:03:19.712
It's like an animal instinct almost to protect oneself.

00:03:19.744 --> 00:03:28.416
To put up walls and barriers, to turn defensively against the world, to become, Kervatos and say, precisely out of fear.

00:03:29.088 --> 00:03:31.456
What does Jesus say? Perfect love.

00:03:31.424 --> 00:03:36.192
It casts out all fear. That's a key insight there, it seems to me.

00:03:36.352 --> 00:03:44.768
Now, this is also why the opposite of pride, the antidote to pride, is called humility. And we automatically have a kind of,

00:03:44.544 --> 00:03:49.408
Superficial understanding of humility, but the key is in the etymology.

00:03:49.664 --> 00:03:52.640
Homo melitas comes from hummus

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:54.816
Which means like the soil.

00:03:55.136 --> 00:03:58.464
It's funny, isn't it? He wouldn't think of that. But the soil

00:03:58.656 --> 00:04:00.640
To be humble.

00:04:01.024 --> 00:04:05.856
is to be in touch with reality. See, it's,

00:04:05.632 --> 00:04:11.136
literally down to earth, or to use our language, grounded.

00:04:11.104 --> 00:04:12.864
See, a humble person

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:21.056
is able to get out of the black hole of self-regard and enter into being, into reality.

00:04:20.704 --> 00:04:22.048
In that sense,

00:04:21.824 --> 00:04:24.128
Homeless, the ground, the earth.

00:04:24.256 --> 00:04:28.896
Think of a farmer with his hands in the dirt. He's in touch with reality.

00:04:28.864 --> 00:04:30.688
That's the humble.

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:31.776
person.

00:04:32.352 --> 00:04:34.720
You know, somebody Jordan Peterson said,

00:04:34.432 --> 00:04:39.264
A while ago, he might have said it, in fact, in this very room in a podcast that we did.

00:04:39.456 --> 00:04:40.608
He said,

00:04:40.672 --> 00:04:42.784
Self-regard

00:04:43.424 --> 00:04:48.000
Psychologically speaking, is identical to misery.

00:04:48.800 --> 00:04:54.592
it seems, it strikes me as dead right and very much in line with what I've been talking about.

00:04:54.368 --> 00:05:04.416
Self-regard, when I'm looking inward, is psychologically speaking equivalent to misery. Think for a second, everybody, the best moments in life

00:05:03.936 --> 00:05:05.440
In your life.

00:05:05.504 --> 00:05:10.080
I will guarantee you it's when you are least aware of yourself.

00:05:10.656 --> 00:05:13.888
100%. When you're not looking in, you're looking out, right?

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:21.568
you're not preoccupied with what's what's affecting you and what's threatening you and all that. you're you've forgotten that.

00:05:21.408 --> 00:05:25.600
And you're in touch with almost with the ground with reality.

00:05:26.144 --> 00:05:29.312
That's what we're talking about. That's the humility of

00:05:29.024 --> 00:05:31.232
that stands against pride.

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:34.208
Okay. Now, that's the general principle, okay?

00:05:34.112 --> 00:05:42.592
The gospel gives us, in typical biblical fashion, the Bible doesn't usually engage in sort of philosophical analysis. It tells stories.

00:05:42.432 --> 00:05:45.408
And we've got this great story that Jesus tells.

00:05:45.088 --> 00:05:47.488
That's right to this point, though.

00:05:47.744 --> 00:05:48.704
Listen.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:52.608
He says, when you're invited by someone to a wedding banquet,

00:05:52.896 --> 00:05:55.968
Do not recline a table in the place of honor.

00:05:56.256 --> 00:05:58.912
Rather, when you're invited, go and take

00:05:58.656 --> 00:06:00.352
The lowest place.

00:06:00.768 --> 00:06:06.592
Well, he's drawing from his own time and culture, but it should be pretty obvious what he's talking about.

00:06:06.496 --> 00:06:11.456
So a wedding banquet, everybody's there. It's a very public place.

00:06:11.808 --> 00:06:14.272
What do we prideful people want?

00:06:14.112 --> 00:06:18.752
Because we're afraid, okay, I get it, we're afraid. And so we want to, we want to,

00:06:18.496 --> 00:06:20.416
elevate ourselves.

00:06:20.512 --> 00:06:21.536
We,

00:06:21.344 --> 00:06:24.416
We protect ourselves by elevating ourselves.

00:06:24.672 --> 00:06:27.392
Look at me. I'm in the...

00:06:27.232 --> 00:06:33.600
I'm at the prime position. I'm at the top table. And so we jockey to get precisely in that position.

00:06:33.632 --> 00:06:34.656
Physician.

00:06:35.616 --> 00:06:39.904
Now, take your walk of life. You can see this everywhere it seems to me.

00:06:39.968 --> 00:06:46.304
People trying to get into the higher position and more to it in a way that's publicly visible.

00:06:46.272 --> 00:06:56.320
That's why this wedding banquet image is so good, because think of a bustling room full of people. It's not like I've quietly and privately moved into the highest position. I'm publicly...

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:05.376
publicly, visibly in the higher position. And everyone can see, oh, he's at the top table as opposed to everybody else at lower tables.

00:07:05.728 --> 00:07:09.504
Well, that's a very familiar move.

00:07:09.568 --> 00:07:10.560
Um,

00:07:11.264 --> 00:07:16.896
Can I give you some examples from the world that I know best, which is the ecclesiastical world?

00:07:16.544 --> 00:07:26.592
Now, I'm not picking on the church here. This is the world I know best. But pick your world. I mean, it's available everywhere human beings are operating.

00:07:26.112 --> 00:07:26.816
Operating.

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:28.928
But the Catholic Church

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:31.520
Is a very hierarchical institution.

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:41.888
We got deacons, we got priests, we got Monsignors, we got auxiliary bishops, we got bishops, we got archbishops, we got cardinals. And among the cardinals, you got cardinal deacons, cardinal priests, and cardinal bishops

00:07:41.408 --> 00:07:47.680
Hope, at the top of the hierarchy. We have a very hierarchically arranged setup.

00:07:47.584 --> 00:07:50.816
Now, is that bad in itself? No, it's not bad in itself. Okay.

00:07:51.232 --> 00:07:53.632
But what does it set up?

00:07:53.376 --> 00:07:54.368
well.

00:07:54.176 --> 00:08:01.248
Everyone in the church is prideful. And I don't mean that it's critical of the church. I mean, all of us human beings wrestle with pride.

00:08:01.088 --> 00:08:06.176
So when you bring pride now into that scenario, what's going to happen?

00:08:06.528 --> 00:08:10.912
Well, everyone's jockeying for the highest position.

00:08:10.816 --> 00:08:17.760
Who's rising in the hierarchy? Who's going down in the hierarchy? Who's on top? Who's on bottom?

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:24.160
I remember years ago, I was in Rome for something, and I went to this event. It was a talk. It was a talk.

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:34.144
I got there kind of early and the chairs were kind of arranged and I just took a seat not in the first row but kind of up toward the front. I wanted to have a good seat for the time.

00:08:34.016 --> 00:08:44.064
And this little man, senior, came out, I remember. And at the time, I wasn't a bishop. I was just a lowly priest, you know. And he came out and he goes, no, no, no, no, no, padre, padre.

00:08:43.584 --> 00:08:44.320
All right.

00:08:44.096 --> 00:08:45.600
And then he gestured.

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:55.488
Cardinale, Archivescu, Vivescu, Monsignore. He was saying, no, no, this is the section for the cardinals, for the archbishops, for the bishops. And he sent me a

00:08:55.008 --> 00:09:00.448
He, all the way to the back of the room, where the little, you know, prettier, the little priest had to sit. Yeah.

00:09:00.512 --> 00:09:06.912
Okay. That's the way it goes. We tend to play these games regularly.

00:09:07.296 --> 00:09:08.864
Out of a desire

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:19.648
to elevate ourselves, you know? And I wasn't doing it on purpose that time. I just wanted to get a good seat. But the Monsignor was very aware of who belonged and what, you know,

00:09:19.168 --> 00:09:20.640
You know, what position? Yeah.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:30.336
Again, I'm not implying everybody that we shouldn't have hierarchies or that they're bad in themselves. I'm just noticing how we prideful people are.

00:09:30.208 --> 00:09:31.968
End up playing that game.

00:09:32.256 --> 00:09:33.312
Um,

00:09:33.408 --> 00:09:35.456
Now, what's the way...

00:09:35.872 --> 00:09:36.768
Out.

00:09:37.536 --> 00:09:47.584
Well, you know, let me say something. Before I get to the solution, there's one more point I want to make. I've talked before to you about the Wheel of Fortune, right, which is this device in the medieval cathedrals and the top.

00:09:47.104 --> 00:09:57.152
a top-of-the-wheel fortune, someone that's made it. He's the king, and then the wheel turns, and he's lost his crown. And then at the bottom, there's the pauper that has no power. And then the guy who's

00:09:56.672 --> 00:10:02.624
Who's rising up to power and the point is the wheel just keeps turning in life you know that's the way it goes

00:10:02.368 --> 00:10:04.864
Well, the medievals knew this, that

00:10:04.992 --> 00:10:09.184
All the points on the rim of the wheel are points of anxiety.

00:10:10.272 --> 00:10:12.544
But the worst of them all

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:14.944
Is the top of the wheel

00:10:15.392 --> 00:10:18.432
right here at the top of the wheel okay I made it

00:10:18.272 --> 00:10:24.288
But my prideful soul is now satisfied. I'm at the top of the wheel of fortune. I'm in the highest seat.

00:10:23.904 --> 00:10:33.472
Yeah, but you know for sure that all kinds of people underneath you are jockeying for position and trying to knock you out of that perch.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:35.040
That's the least

00:10:35.104 --> 00:10:37.856
A comfortable place of all to be. A place of all to be.

00:10:38.656 --> 00:10:42.528
I think you're of the great line from Oscar Wilde.

00:10:42.848 --> 00:10:46.720
He said the only thing worse than not getting what you want

00:10:47.648 --> 00:10:49.568
Is getting what you want.

00:10:49.696 --> 00:10:59.456
I found that played out in many ways in my own life and the lives of others. Oh, the one thing I want, I'll be finally satisfied.

00:10:59.936 --> 00:11:01.280
and i get it.

00:11:01.056 --> 00:11:06.208
And I'm happy for maybe a day or two. And then I realize that

00:11:06.464 --> 00:11:09.280
That's the worst thing that could have happened to me.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.768
That's now put me in the worst possible position.

00:11:13.728 --> 00:11:15.456
So, what did Jesus say?

00:11:15.968 --> 00:11:22.272
You know, I know when you come in a room and you're at the banquet and I know what your pride dictates. Take the highest place.

00:11:22.336 --> 00:11:23.296
No, no.

00:11:23.552 --> 00:11:25.376
On purpose,

00:11:26.272 --> 00:11:27.968
Take the lowest place.

00:11:28.832 --> 00:11:30.080
On purpose.

00:11:30.592 --> 00:11:31.552
How come?

00:11:31.936 --> 00:11:32.992
because because

00:11:33.152 --> 00:11:35.104
You're consciously

00:11:35.008 --> 00:11:37.344
Opting out of the game.

00:11:38.592 --> 00:11:43.264
See, the point is that playing the game at all

00:11:44.032 --> 00:11:45.856
We'll get you in trouble.

00:11:45.504 --> 00:11:48.640
F. Whether you're good at it or bad at it.

00:11:48.544 --> 00:11:56.288
Whether you succeed at it or fail at it, playing the game of pride and self-elevation and seeking honor

00:11:56.352 --> 00:11:58.848
Is going to harm you.

00:11:59.008 --> 00:11:59.968
um.

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:03.040
I'm going to date myself here, but there was a movie.

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:05.536
from the early eighties, I think.

00:12:06.016 --> 00:12:08.032
It was called War Games.

00:12:07.936 --> 00:12:17.984
And it was kind of in the early, early days of computers. We're all kind of fascinated by computers. And it's about a kid that hacks into the NORAD, you know, National Defense System and is a...

00:12:17.504 --> 00:12:26.624
And is affecting our nuclear defense and all this. Well, the movie Climax, as I remember in this great scene, they're inside of NORAD and, and, uh,

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:28.512
The scenarios are playing out.

00:12:28.416 --> 00:12:38.464
of nuclear attacks, if you know, American tax first or Russia tax first and this city, the next city and what would happen. And then they're looking at the board and all these scenarios, hundreds, hundreds of

00:12:37.984 --> 00:12:43.872
It's hundreds, thousands playing out before them of who's going to win a nuclear war. And then it ends there.

00:12:43.808 --> 00:12:48.160
And up on the board, or maybe it was a voice that announced it, saying,

00:12:48.384 --> 00:12:52.160
The the only winning strategy,

00:12:52.416 --> 00:12:54.400
is not to play the game.

00:12:55.136 --> 00:12:59.552
Well, I go by that line a lot because it applies in the spiritual order.

00:13:00.096 --> 00:13:05.536
There are games, everybody, that we all play. We're all sinners, and we're all full of pride.

00:13:05.344 --> 00:13:12.512
And we're fearful. And so we aggrandize ourselves and we defend ourselves and we jockey for position.

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:13.504
okay.

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:14.528
i get it.

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:19.680
But the only way to win that game is not to play it.

00:13:20.832 --> 00:13:22.656
Get off the board.

00:13:23.328 --> 00:13:33.376
Right. Get off the grid completely. And you know what I'm talking about. Actually, you're a real estate developer. You're a dentist. You're an academician. You're a private investor.

00:13:32.896 --> 00:13:37.088
20% investor. Any walk of life, you know what I'm talking about here.

00:13:36.928 --> 00:13:40.416
And you can spend the whole of your life

00:13:39.968 --> 00:13:42.176
playing this game.

00:13:42.272 --> 00:13:51.488
100% of who's up, who's down, who's gaining, who's losing. Hey, I'm on top and everyone sees me. And before you know it, you're plummeting down again. See, I'm

00:13:51.264 --> 00:13:56.288
Don't play the game. So that's why Jesus says, on purpose,

00:13:56.352 --> 00:13:58.336
Take the lowest place.

00:13:58.496 --> 00:14:00.000
on purpose.

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:02.912
Don't play the game.

00:14:03.488 --> 00:14:05.632
Here's a way to sum it up.

00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:10.368
A lot of us sinners, we spend a lot of time and a lot of energy.

00:14:10.112 --> 00:14:16.160
Trying to please people around us or make people around us think we're really something.

00:14:17.632 --> 00:14:20.512
Forget it. it is an utter waste of time.

00:14:21.696 --> 00:14:26.272
You're handing the whole of your happiness over to the fickle

00:14:26.432 --> 00:14:28.128
Attitudes of other people.

00:14:28.672 --> 00:14:29.984
Don't play that game.

00:14:30.144 --> 00:14:31.616
Rather, seek

00:14:31.552 --> 00:14:33.568
only to please God.

00:14:34.912 --> 00:14:36.736
That's the route of the humble person.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:40.576
And trust me, you'll be infinitely happier.

00:14:41.024 --> 00:14:42.272
And God bless you.

00:14:46.208 --> 00:14:50.432
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

00:14:50.176 --> 00:14:55.808
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.
